          "body": "The psalm opens with a question: 'Why do the nations rage?' (v.1). The question is not bewildered — it is diagnostic. The psalmist already knows the answer: the nations' rage is against YHWH and His Anointed (v.2), and its aim is autonomy — 'let us tear their fetters apart and cast away their cords from us' (v.3). Human rebellion against divine authority is not random social disorder; it is a theological posture. The nations perceive God's law and His king as bondage. What they are determined to throw off is precisely what would sustain them. The irony is signaled immediately: their plotting is 'in vain' (riq, v.1) — emptiness, futility, waste. The rebellion is exposed as futile before the narrator even describes it fully. The New Testament reads Psalm 2:1-2 as the explicit script of the events of Good Friday: Herod and Pilate, Gentiles and peoples of Israel, gathered against Jesus (Acts 4:25-27). The psalm's 'why' finds its deepest historical answer at Golgotha."
