          "title": "God enthroned — laughter, wrath, and the installed King",
          "body": "The psalm's most important rhetorical device is the sudden cut in verse 4 from earth to heaven. The nations are in uproar; the kings are taking their stand; the rulers are conspiring — and then, without transition: 'He who sits in the heavens laughs.' The contrast is absolute. Their noise is met by His laughter. Not anxiety. Not emergency. Laughter. The theological point is ontological: there is an infinite distance between the Creator enthroned in heaven and creatures conspiring in dust, and that distance makes the conspiracy absurd. YHWH's laughter is not cruelty — it is the natural response of one who holds all power to those who imagine they can threaten it. But the laughter does not mean the rebellion is ignored. Verse 5 pivots: 'Then He will speak to them in His anger and terrify them in His fury.' The God who laughs also judges. And His answer to the whole conspiracy is a single sovereign act: 'I have installed My King upon Zion, My holy mountain' (v.6). The perfect-tense verb is the psalm's central declaration: before the nations plotted, God acted. The installation is done."
