          "body": "Verses 7-9 introduce a third voice — the Installed King Himself speaks, reciting the divine decree he has received. 'You are My Son, today I have begotten You' (v.7). In its original Davidic context, this decree marked the covenantal adoption of the Israelite king, drawn from the language of 2 Samuel 7:14 ('I will be his father, and he will be My son'). But the New Testament understands the fulfillment to run deeper. Hebrews 1:5 and 5:5 cite this verse to establish the Son's eternal and unique divine sonship; Acts 13:33 applies the 'today' to the resurrection as the decisive moment of the Son's public enthronement as the God-Man. The decree is followed by a promise of scope: ask, and receive the nations as inheritance and the ends of the earth as possession (v.8). What the nations were plotting to escape (domination by YHWH's king) is precisely what is decreed for them — not as cruelty but as the rightful ordering of creation. Verse 9's rod of iron and shattered pottery (cited in Revelation 2:27; 12:5; 19:15) describe the unconditional nature of the Messiah's final dominion: no rival kingdom survives the consummation."
